00:51.680 --> 00:56.040
We've been talking about what a network is, and that is a bunch of devices that are connected

00:56.040 --> 00:59.120
to each other for the purpose of communications.

00:59.120 --> 01:04.120
But companies today have a need to connect devices across wide areas.

01:04.120 --> 01:10.640
So if there's a need to connect devices in one city to devices across another city,

01:10.640 --> 01:17.120
or even another country, for example, there are technologies that allow this.

01:17.120 --> 01:20.720
That's what we call wide-area network technologies.

01:20.720 --> 01:24.880
So there's different options that companies can use, and these are some of them.

01:24.880 --> 01:29.600
We can use modems, although that wouldn't be very good anymore.

01:29.600 --> 01:31.640
But there are other options.

01:31.640 --> 01:38.240
Typically, these are some of the options that you can lease from the service providers that

01:38.240 --> 01:43.600
have built capabilities to allow companies to connect across wide areas.

01:43.600 --> 01:46.520
So we have dedicated lease lines as an option.

01:46.520 --> 01:54.160
Those are lines like T1s, T2s, T3s that allow connections across wide areas.

01:54.160 --> 02:00.240
We can also use satellite and other wireless links, like microwave capabilities.

02:00.240 --> 02:06.280
But the problem with those is, typically, you'll have large footprints, but also a lot

02:06.280 --> 02:12.200
of interference from nature and some other things that may impact the quality and the integrity

02:12.200 --> 02:16.400
of the communications that are going across those wide areas.

02:16.400 --> 02:21.960
What most companies use today is what we call data packet carrier services.

02:21.960 --> 02:27.520
And so these are networks that have been created by the service providers themselves,

02:27.520 --> 02:30.040
like AT&T and so on.

02:30.040 --> 02:36.720
And what they do is they will lease connections to you across these data networks that have

02:36.720 --> 02:42.120
been built specifically to allow connections across wide areas.

02:42.120 --> 02:46.080
And just like anything else, these technologies have evolved.

02:46.080 --> 02:53.320
The original data packet carrier services that were offered to us by these providers was

02:53.320 --> 02:55.080
X25.

02:55.080 --> 03:04.320
X25 is a data packet carrier service that sends information across the network by using

03:04.320 --> 03:05.320
packets.

03:05.320 --> 03:10.680
In fact, all of these are their packet switch networks, but they're meant to allow companies

03:10.680 --> 03:13.400
to allow to connect across wide areas.

03:13.400 --> 03:18.600
Now because X25 was the original one, it's really an older technology, but it's still

03:18.600 --> 03:25.560
considered by many to be the best one to handle error correction and problems that you

03:25.560 --> 03:30.640
may have in transmitting information across those networks.

03:30.640 --> 03:35.960
But it requires a high overhead in order to achieve that really good error correction

03:35.960 --> 03:37.200
that it offers us.

03:37.200 --> 03:39.440
And so the speeds are very limited.

03:39.440 --> 03:44.480
There's a lot of overhead, but it's still the best network for error correction.

03:44.480 --> 03:50.360
In fact, what happened, if you look at this historically, is the industry created frame

03:50.360 --> 03:54.640
relay to really replace X25.

03:54.640 --> 04:00.440
And so that was a better technology that didn't do as well for error correction, but certainly

04:00.440 --> 04:02.120
gave us faster speeds.

04:02.120 --> 04:07.120
And in fact, that was replaced by what we call ATM.

04:07.120 --> 04:11.800
How was one of the latest technologies that we've already had for a large number of

04:11.800 --> 04:12.800
years?

04:12.800 --> 04:17.480
Today, we have a better technology for this, and it's called MPLS.

04:17.480 --> 04:22.960
And one of the improvements that they've made with MPLS is not only speed and quality

04:22.960 --> 04:28.640
of service, but they can also offer us some built-in security, and this is what you want

04:28.640 --> 04:36.520
to remember, MPLS networks will use what are called forwarding tables and labeling schemes

04:36.520 --> 04:43.240
to ensure that, for example, our connection that we're using across the MPLS network that

04:43.240 --> 04:45.960
belongs to a provider.

04:45.960 --> 04:53.480
Our path that our information is using across their network cannot be touched by anyone

04:53.480 --> 04:54.480
else.

04:54.480 --> 05:00.140
And so the providers will guarantee that our path and the devices that are using our

05:00.140 --> 05:07.300
path cannot be touched or used by anyone else while they're being used for our transmission.

05:07.300 --> 05:12.380
So they can guarantee that the path that our information is taking is ours.

05:12.380 --> 05:16.420
And so they'll say things like, you don't need to encrypt because nobody can get to your

05:16.420 --> 05:17.820
information.

05:17.820 --> 05:23.140
But I know companies that are using MPLS and still encrypt the information because even

05:23.140 --> 05:28.180
though the providers will tell us that nobody can get to those paths, there is one entity

05:28.180 --> 05:31.340
that can, and that is the provider themselves.

05:31.340 --> 05:35.620
And just because we're paying them for a service doesn't mean that we should trust them to

05:35.620 --> 05:38.340
be able to see our information.

05:38.340 --> 05:45.420
And so it may be required that even though MPLS has built-in security that we would still

05:45.420 --> 05:50.700
use authentication and encryption to protect that traffic based on its value.

05:50.700 --> 05:56.780
Now what you want to remember about MPLS is that it uses technology that is forwarding

05:56.780 --> 06:03.500
tables and labeling schemes to ensure that those paths are our paths and nobody can

06:03.500 --> 06:04.700
get to them.

06:04.700 --> 06:11.260
And that's the built-in security that is part of what we call MPLS networks for wide-area

06:11.260 --> 06:12.820
network capabilities.

